    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_118553275" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/118553275" />
    <a title="James" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/911622-james"><img alt="James" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1620539405p2/911622.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/118553275?book_show_action=true">Aug 25, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="James" class="user" itemprop="url" name="James" href="/user/show/911622-james">James</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer118553275" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10221802364714268361">The first installment in a trilogy telling of a fantastic realm defined by an epic struggle between Dark and Light powers. The Dark powers are so draconian that even their supreme Goddess makes an appearance in the form of a dragon. Like the Chinese Legalists, they rule through terror, believing where there are no small crimes there will be no large crimes. Therefore, do in anyone who does not pay taxes or looks at you in the wrong way. <br/><br/>Their antagonists, those on the Light side of the Force, ha</span>
  <span id="freeText10221802364714268361" style="display:none">The first installment in a trilogy telling of a fantastic realm defined by an epic struggle between Dark and Light powers. The Dark powers are so draconian that even their supreme Goddess makes an appearance in the form of a dragon. Like the Chinese Legalists, they rule through terror, believing where there are no small crimes there will be no large crimes. Therefore, do in anyone who does not pay taxes or looks at you in the wrong way. <br /><br />Their antagonists, those on the Light side of the Force, have more humane rules of engagement, without being wimps—especially the women—who constantly exude so much sarcasm that they vibe more attitude than the Crips and the Bloods put together. If this seems odd, it is because even the women on the Good side of the Force find themselves in an environment where they often feel as voiceless and patronized as those on planet Earth. <br /><br />The reader is given ample clues that this will not always be the case.<br /><br />Told in a page-turning style that yin-yangs back and forth between the Good and Evil realms, the perfect Manichaean dualism is problematized by an ethical switch-hitter motivated, it seems, more by nature than by nurture. <br /><br />This reader eagerly awaits the release of the second volume, over which the authress is reportedly brooding, within the confines of her darkly gargoyled chamber.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10221802364714268361" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

